{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519605"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:13:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:13:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13048"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13048"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.03,0.61,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5485"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113189"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5485"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13048"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95216"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1044"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9320"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10272"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46021"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113189"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with symptoms of bloating, nausea and abdominal discomfort over the past few months. She has no relevant medical history, has an Implanon in situ and takes no regular medications. She states that her brother was diagnosed with coeliac disease a few years ago and she is worried that she has the same condition. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most appropriate to confirm the diagnosis of coeliac disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-tissue transglutaminase antibody level","Colonoscopy with visualisation of the large bowel","Endoscopy with biopsy","Anti\u2013deamidated gliadin antibody level","HLA gene testing"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of investigations that help assess for coeliac disease. However, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebiopsy of the duodenal mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E is necessary to confirm the diagnosis. At least six biopsies should be taken and the disease is characterised by the presence of intraepithelial lymphocytosis (IEL\u0026gt;30/100 epithelial cells), lamina propria inflammation and villous atrophy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerology testing for \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-tissue transglutaminase antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E and\u003Cstrong\u003E anti\u2013deamidated gliadin antibody\u003C/strong\u003E is often the first step to help narrow down the diagnosis however is not conclusive with biopsy required for confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHLA gene testing\u003C/strong\u003E is not diagnostic as it only suggests gene susceptibility. However, coeliac disease can be ruled out if this test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf coeliac disease is ruled out, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E may be performed to explore other causes of abdominal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFinally, it is important to note that in practice, endoscopies may not always be performed. If a patient presents with classical symptoms (with no red flags) and positive results in other supplementary tests (e.g. serology), a gluten-free diet may be trialled. If successful, further investigation may not necessarily considered. However, this varies in relation to the clinical scenario and the opinion of the treating medical professional.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Biopsy of the duodenal mucosa is necessary for diagnosis of coeliac disease"],"references":["Interpreting tests for coeliac disease [Internet]. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/january-february/interpreting-tests-for-coeliac-disease-1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95216"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13048"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95216"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-10T11:55:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T12:11:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5485"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113189"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null